{"id":"2204.01619","submitter":"Tamara Broderick","authors":"Nicholas Bonaker, Emli-Mari Nel, Keith Vertanen, Tamara Broderick","title":"A Performance Evaluation of Nomon: A Flexible Interface for Noisy\n  Single-Switch Users","comments":"Appearing in CHI 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.HC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Some individuals with motor impairments communicate using a single switch --\nsuch as a button click, air puff, or blink. Row-column scanning provides a\nmethod for choosing items arranged in a grid using a single switch. An\nalternative, Nomon, allows potential selections to be arranged arbitrarily\nrather than requiring a grid (as desired for gaming, drawing, etc.) -- and\nprovides an alternative probabilistic selection method. While past results\nsuggest that Nomon may be faster and easier to use than row-column scanning, no\nwork has yet quantified performance of the two methods over longer time periods\nor in tasks beyond writing. In this paper, we also develop and validate a\nwebcam-based switch that allows a user without a motor impairment to\napproximate the response times of a motor-impaired single switch user; although\nthe approximation is not a replacement for testing with single-switch users, it\nallows us to better initialize, calibrate, and evaluate our method. Over 10\nsessions with the webcam switch, we found users typed faster and more easily\nwith Nomon than with row-column scanning. The benefits of Nomon were even more\npronounced in a picture-selection task. Evaluation and feedback from a\nmotor-impaired switch user further supports the promise of Nomon.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Apr 2022 16:11:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-05"}
