{"id":"2204.01646","submitter":"Ryan Martin","authors":"Vaidehi Dixit and Ryan Martin","title":"A PRticle filter algorithm for nonparametric estimation of multivariate\n  mixing distributions","comments":"22 pages, 5 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.CO stat.ME","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Predictive recursion (PR) is a fast, recursive algorithm that gives a smooth\nestimate of the mixing distribution under the general mixture model. However,\nthe PR algorithm requires evaluation of a normalizing constant at each\niteration. When the support of the mixing distribution is of relatively low\ndimension, this is not a problem since quadrature methods can be used and are\nvery efficient. But when the support is of higher dimension, quadrature methods\nare inefficient and there is no obvious Monte Carlo-based alternative. In this\npaper, we propose a new strategy, which we refer to as a PRticle filter,\nwherein we augment the basic PR algorithm with a filtering mechanism that\nadaptively reweights an initial set of particles along the updating sequence\nwhich are used to obtain Monte Carlo approximations of the normalizing\nconstants. Convergence properties of the PRticle filter approximation are\nestablished and its empirical accuracy is demonstrated with simulation studies\nand a marked spatial point process data analysis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Apr 2022 16:54:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 20 Nov 2022 21:57:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-22"}
