{"id":"2204.01743","submitter":"Nicholas Early","authors":"Freddy Cachazo, Nick Early","title":"Biadjoint Scalars and Associahedra from Residues of Generalized\n  Amplitudes","comments":"31 pages, 1 figure. Ancillary notebook with data and calculations","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Generalized scattering amplitudes $m^{(k)}_n$, discovered by Cachazo, Early,\nGuevara and Mizera (CEGM), form a symmetric hierarchy which is essentially\nrecursive in nature. In the Generalized Feynman Diagrams framework, $m^{(k)}_n$\nbecomes an \\textit{interpolation} of $n$ copies of $m^{(k-1)}_{n-1}$ which can\nbe reconstituted from compatible combinatorial data on the facets of the\nhypersimplex $\\Delta_{k,n}$.\n  The interpolation, solved by CEGM generalized amplitudes, is tightly\nconstrained: the combinatorial data on the $n$ facets of $\\Delta_{k,n}$ must\nextend into its interior to a particular kind of subdivision that is matroidal\nand \\textit{regular}: the internal faces of the subdivision should be\nprojections of the bends of a piecewise linear surface over $\\Delta_{k,n}$.\nNumerous physical and combinatorial questions have been raised; one of these\nwas to determine if and how the standard biadjoint scalar amplitude $m^{(2)}_n$\nitself exists systematically \"inside\" $m^{(k)}_n$.\n  In this paper we find an entire forest of identifications of $m^{(2)}_n$ with\nmulti-dimensional residues of $m^{(3)}_n$, where the kinematic space for each\n$m^{(2)}_n$ maps into a twisted chart in the bulk kinematic space. We find\n$n\\cdot C^{(2)}_{n-5}$ such identifications, where $C^{(2)}_p$ are the Catalan\nnumbers. We show that after a suitable one-parameter deformation which we call\na \\textit{parallel hard limit}, these residues aggregate to produce $n$\ndistinct, cyclically permuted copies of a product $m^{(2)}_n \\cdot\nm^{(2)}_{n-3}$.\n  We propose a gene